FoodHub Data Analysis Project¶

Project Overview¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day, and lots of students and busy professionals rely on these restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Food aggregators like FoodHub offer access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app, helping customers order food easily online.

This project analyzes data from FoodHub to find trends and patterns in food orders. By answering key business questions, this analysis helps FoodHub improve customer experience and business strategy.

Objectives¶

  • Understand the structure of the FoodHub order dataset
  • Explore the data using summary statistics and visualizations
  • Identify trends in restaurant and cuisine popularity
  • Analyze customer ratings and delivery/performance times
  • Provide recommendations for FoodHub to enhance business operations

1. Understanding the Structure of the Data¶

Data Description¶

The dataset contains the following columns:

Column Name Description
order_id Unique ID for each order
customer_id Unique ID for each customer
restaurant_name Name of the restaurant
cuisine_type Type of cuisine ordered
cost_of_the_order Cost of the order
day_of_the_week Indicates whether it's a weekday or a weekend order
rating Customer rating (out of 5)
food_preparation_time Time taken (in minutes) to prepare the food
delivery_time Time taken (in minutes) to deliver the food

Explanation:¶

  • order_id and customer_id are numbers and used to identify orders and customers.
  • restaurant_name and cuisine_type are words/text (strings).
  • cost_of_the_order and rating are numbers with decimals (float).
  • day_of_the_week is a word/text (string).
  • food_preparation_time and delivery_time are whole numbers (integer).

2. Univariate Data Analysis¶

2.1 Overview¶

In this section, each variable in the FoodHub dataset is explored individually using visualizations and summary statistics. The goal is to understand the distribution, central tendency, and key patterns for all major numerical and categorical variables.

2.2 Numerical Variables¶

a) Cost of the Order¶

  • Visualized using a histogram and described with summary statistics (mean, median, std, min, max).
  • Title should read: Distribution of Cost of Order
  • Axes should be clearly labeled (Cost ($) and Number of Orders).
  • Markdown summary should mention if the data is right-skewed (longer tail to the right), left-skewed, or symmetrical, and note any outliers or typical range for most orders..

Section 2 Summary: Key Univariate Insights¶

  • Order Cost: Most customer orders are in the lower-to-mid price range, with a few higher-priced outliers. The distribution is slightly right-skewed.
  • Preparation and Delivery Times: Typical preparation times are quite consistent, with most orders prepared in about 2530 minutes. Delivery times are also reliable, with most taking around 25 minutes.
  • Customer Ratings: A majority of orders receive the highest rating (5 stars), indicating strong customer satisfaction. However, a notable portion of orders do not have ratings, which may limit detailed quality analysis.
  • Restaurant & Cuisine Preferences: A small group of restaurants and American cuisine dominate order volumes, suggesting clear customer favorites.
  • Ordering Patterns by Day: Orders are significantly higher on weekends compared to weekdays, which has implications for staffing and marketing efforts.

These insights provide an initial understanding of customer behavior and operational performance on the FoodHub platform. The next section will explore how these variables relate to each other (multivariate analysis).

3.2 Bivariate Analysis¶

a) Comparison of Average Order Cost: Weekdays vs. Weekends¶

This analysis examines whether customers tend to spend more on food orders during weekends compared to weekdays. By comparing the average cost of orders for each period, we aim to understand if purchasing behavior shifts with the day of the week, which could inform promotions, resource allocation, and menu strategies.

On average, orders placed on weekends are slightly more expensive ($16.57) compared to weekdays ($16.31).

The difference is ~$0.26, which may indicate:

  • More leisurely or bulk purchases on weekends.

  • Promotions or discounts affecting weekday behavior.

  • Slight customer behavior shift based on free time.

This plot investigates whether the amount of time taken by a restaurant to prepare food influences the customers rating. We look for patterns or trends indicating if longer or shorter preparation times affect overall customer satisfaction as reflected in their ratings.

  • The food preparation time ranges from ~20 to 35 minutes, but the rating doesn't clearly go up or down based on it.

  • This suggests: There is no strong correlation between how long the food takes to prepare and the rating customers give.

f) Correlation Heatmap Between Key Numerical Variables¶

This heatmap displays the pairwise correlations between the main numerical variables: cost of the order, customer rating, food preparation time, and delivery time. By examining the strength and direction of these correlations, we can identify whether any of these factors are strongly related, such as if higher costs tend to come with higher ratings or if longer preparation times are linked to longer deliveries. This analysis helps reveal which metrics operate independently and which may influence one another.

In [26]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Select relevant numerical columns
num_df = df[["cost_of_the_order", "rating", "food_preparation_time", "delivery_time"]]

# Create the correlation heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(num_df.corr(), annot=True, cmap="coolwarm", linewidths=0.5, fmt=".2f")
plt.title("Correlation Between Key Variables")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observation:¶

  • There is no strong correlation among the numeric variables: Cost, Rating, Preparation Time, and Delivery Time. Here's a breakdown of each relationship:

  • Cost vs. Rating: The correlation is very low and positive (+0.034), which means spending more does not lead to better customer ratings.

  • Cost vs. Preparation Time: A negligible positive correlation (+0.042) suggests that higher-cost orders might take slightly more time to prepare, but the relationship is very weak.

  • Cost vs. Delivery Time: There's a very weak negative correlation (0.030), meaning cost has almost no effect on delivery time.

  • Rating vs. Preparation Time: Correlation is close to zero (0.006), indicating that how fast a dish is prepared does not influence customer ratings.

  • Rating vs. Delivery Time: Again, the correlation is almost nonexistent (0.010), showing that customers don't rate differently based on delivery speed.

  • Preparation Time vs. Delivery Time: A weak positive correlation (+0.011) implies that even if preparation takes longer, it doesnt strongly affect delivery time.

5. Conclusion and Recommendations¶

5.1 Key Insights¶

1. Customer Ordering Patterns¶

  • The majority of FoodHub customers place orders in the affordable range, with most individual order costs falling between $10 and $25. *There is a clear surge in orders during weekends, accounting for nearly 70% of total volumehighlighting strong lifestyle-based demand peaks.

2. Cuisine and Restaurant Popularity¶

  • American cuisine is by far the most popular, followed by Japanese and Italian. Other cuisines such as Vietnamese and Spanish are rarely ordered.
  • A few restaurants, especially Shake Shack and Blue Ribbon Sushi, dominate ordering activity. The top 10 restaurants account for a significant proportion of all orders, indicating high brand loyalty among customers.

3. Timeliness of Service¶

  • Preparation Times: Most food is prepared within 2035 minutes, showing reliable kitchen efficiency across restaurants. *Delivery Times: Deliveries are typically made within 1533 minutes, but delivery times are, on average, 23 minutes longer on weekends compared to weekdays. This suggests mild operational bottlenecks during peak demand periods.

4. Customer Satisfaction¶

  • The majority of post-order ratings are clustered at the highest value (5 stars), indicating broad customer satisfaction. Only a very small proportion of ratings are 3 or below. *Notably, a considerable portion of orders lack customer ratings, limiting the ability to assess dissatisfaction or improvement areas in detail.

5. Relationships Between Variables¶

  • There is no strong correlation between order cost or preparation/delivery time and customer satisfaction, suggesting that timely and efficient service is generally delivered across all order price ranges.
  • Pairwise analysis shows that food prep time and delivery time are somewhat related, but neither consistently predicts ratings.

6. Outliers and Anomalies¶

  • The data shows isolated cases of longer-than-average delivery or preparation times, but these are infrequent and do not significantly distort overall trends. *Some high-rated restaurants achieve these scores with only a small number of reviews, suggesting sample size should be considered before drawing firm conclusions on restaurant performance.

5.2 Recommendations¶

1. Enhance Weekend Operations¶

  • Reinforce delivery logistics and staffing on weekends to accommodate higher order volumes and to address the slightly longer delivery times.
  • Introduce dedicated Weekend Specials or family deals to further leverage the surge in demand without overwhelming existing infrastructure.

2. Increase Customer Feedback Participation¶

  • Implement nudges via the FoodHub app or through follow-up notifications to encourage more customers to leave ratings after order completion.
  • Offer small incentives (points, coupons, or discounts) to customers who submit feedback, aiming to collect a more balanced and representative set of ratings.

3. Leverage Top-Performing Partners¶

  • Collaborate closely with the top 10 restaurants and the most popular cuisine segments (especially American) for exclusive promotions, loyalty rewards, or co-branded marketing campaigns.
  • Use these partnerships to negotiate better rates or improved service guarantees, benefiting both FoodHub and its customer base.

4. Nurture Emerging and Niche Cuisines¶

  • Consider targeted marketing for less-ordered cuisines (e.g., Vietnamese, Spanish), such as time-limited promotions, bundled offers, or features in the app to stimulate trial and broaden FoodHubs appeal.

5. Investigate Operational Outliers¶

  • Regularly review and address the root causes behind any sporadic long delivery or food preparation times, especially during weekends or specific high-demand hours.
  • Introduce real-time analytics and alerts to proactively address and resolve service delays as they occur.

6. Balance Promotions Between Volume and Quality¶

  • When designing promotional campaigns, balance focus between high-volume (popular) restaurants/cuisines and highly-rated, but less-frequented, partners to achieve both repeat sales and overall user satisfaction.

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • Demand surges on weekends and for American cuisine and a handful of top restaurants.
  • Most customers leave high ratings, though feedback rates could be improved for deeper insights.
  • Service times are consistent; very few orders take more than an hour.
  • Restaurant and cuisine trends are concentrated, with some cuisines and restaurants seeing very few orders.

Recommendations:¶

  • Increase customer feedback participation: Use app nudges or incentives (like loyalty points) to encourage more rating submissions.
  • Boost weekend staffing: To reduce slightly longer delivery times on weekends, optimize delivery force and kitchen preparation efforts.
  • Promote lesser-ordered cuisines: Use bundled offers or special features to stimulate trial of cuisines with lower demand.
  • Leverage high-performing restaurants: Run joint marketing campaigns or promotions with consistently top-rated and high-volume partners.
  • Monitor and address rare long delivery/prep times: Implement tools to flag and analyze any operational outliers for proactive improvement.
